notes: Unlike most other movements, the higher the weight you select for this movement, the easier it is to do. Some gyms have bars instead of pads. If your gym has a bar, place your feet on it instead.

steps: With the bar in front of your nose, grab the bar slightly wider than shoulder-width apart with your palms facing away from you and place your knees on the pad.
Inhale and lower yourself down by allowing your arms to extend.
Continue lowering yourself until your arms are fully extended.
Exhale and pull on the bar to raise yourself up, returning to the starting position.

steps: Position yourself supine over the stability ball so that it presses into your lower back and butt while your torso is leaned back.
With your legs bent in front of you and hands behind your head, exhale and curl your torso forward.
Continue to curl your torso forward while keeping your feet firmly planted on the ground and butt pressed into the ball until your torso is almost upright, allowing your lower back to raise.
Inhale and lower your torso down, returning to the starting position.

notes: By having a spotter help you unrack the barbell at the start of the lift, you will have an easier time during the rest of the lift. Just make sure you don't let them touch the barbell once you start benching unless you need help racking the bar.

steps: Lie flat on the bench so that your head, upper back, and lower back are firmly pressed against the bench and ground at all points, with your feet secured by the pad.
Grab the barbell on the rack at slightly wider than shoulder-width by extending your arms and bring it forward until it is over the middle of your chest with your arms fully extended.
Inhale and lower the barbell towards the middle of your chest.
Continue lowering the barbell until just before it makes contact with your chest.
Exhale and push the barbell upwards returning to the starting position, while keeping your feet, lower back, upper back, and head firmly planted.
After completing all reps, return the barbell to the rack.

Exhale and raise the barbell up towards your shoulders by flexing your arms and driving your elbows backward. Avoid using your legs or back to lift.
Continue until your arms are fully flexed and the barbell cannot be curled any further.
Drive your elbows and arms forward to lift the barbell to the level of your neck.
Inhale and bring your elbows and arms backward and then down, returning the barbell to the starting position.

name: Front Squat
notes: If using a heavy weight with this movement, protect your wrists by resting the barbell on your front shoulders and driving your elbows upwards to allow your hands to hold it there.

primary_muscle_groups.description: Muscles spanning the front of your thigh.

steps: With feet shoulder-width apart, position yourself under the center of the barbell in the rack as you grip the barbell in front of you slightly wider than shoulder-width apart.
Lift the barbell from the rack by partially standing up and taking a step back while squeezing the bar tightly, keeping your wrists tight and firmly in place.
Inhale and break at your hips, sitting down and keeping your torso upright.
Continue until your thighs are at least parallel to the floor.
Exhale and push through your heels to return to the starting position.
After all reps are completed, walk forward to return the barbell to the rack.

steps: With feet shoulder-width apart, position yourself under the center of the barbell in the rack as you place it between your traps and upper back, and grip the barbell slightly wider than shoulder-width apart.
Lift the barbell from the rack by partially standing up and taking a step back while squeezing the barbell tightly and keeping it positioned over your upper back.
While maintaining an upright torso, take a large step forward with one foot, keeping the other foot in place.
Inhale and lower yourself to the ground by bending both legs.
Continue lowering yourself until just before your back knee comes in contact with the ground.
Exhale and push through your front foot to straighten both legs, continuing until your front leg is almost completely straight.
Take a step back returning to the starting position.
Switch sides and repeat the movement after prescribed reps are completed.

steps: Place a barbell on the floor and position yourself over the center of it with your feet shoulder-width apart and shins about 1 inch away from the barbell.
Maintaining a straight back and mostly straight legs, bend down while leaning forward and position your hands on the barbell shoulder-width apart with an overhand grip and fully extended arms.
Exhale and push through your feet to lift the barbell while maintaining a flat back and mostly straight legs.
Continue to raise the barbell up until you are standing upright. Do not lean your torso any further back than your hips.
Inhale and lower the barbell while keeping a flat back and allowing your legs to slightly bend, keeping them mostly straight and returning to the starting position.
Rest the barbell on the ground for 1 second between reps.

steps: Place a barbell on the floor and position yourself over the center of it with your feet much wider than shoulder-width apart and shins about 1 inch away from the barbell.
Maintaining a straight back, bend down with your legs while leaning forward and position your hands on the barbell shoulder-width apart with one palm facing each direction and fully extended arms.
Exhale and push through your feet while extending your legs to begin lifting the barbell while maintaining a flat back.

After the barbell passes your knees, drive through your hips while continuing to extend your legs until you are standing fully upright with your torso in line with the rest of your body. Do not lean further back than this.
Inhale and begin to lower the barbell by bending your legs and lowering your torso while focusing on maintaining a flat back above all else.
Rest the barbell on the floor for 1 second before beginning your next rep.

steps: Maintaining a straight back, bend down with your legs while leaning forward, and grab each handle by your side with fully extended arms so that the cables are next to your midfoot.
Exhale and push through your feet while extending your legs to begin lifting the cables while maintaining a flat back.

After the cable passes your knees, drive through your hips while continuing to extend your legs until you are standing fully upright with your torso in line with the rest of your body. Do not lean further back than this.
Inhale and begin to lower the cable by bending your legs and lowering your torso while focusing on maintaining a flat back above all else.
Returning to the starting position, rest the cables in the bottom position for 1 second before beginning your next rep.

With an overhand grip, exhale and drive your elbow down, tucking it into your side while rotating your palm inward.
Keeping your torso straight, continue to bring your elbow down until it is by your side while you simultaneously drive your shoulder blade down and back.
Inhale and allow your arm to raise, extending it overhead to return to the starting position.
After all reps are completed, switch sides and repeat the movement. 10 reps prescribed means you should perform 10 reps on each side (20 total).

Lift the barbell from the rack by standing up and taking a step back while squeezing the barbell tightly and keeping it over your upper back.
While maintaining an upright torso, lift one leg so that it is placed behind you on a bench, resting the top of your foot on the bench.
Inhale and lower your body by allowing both legs to bend.
Continue to lower your body until your front thigh is at least parallel to the ground.
Exhale and push through your front foot while keeping it flat on the floor to stand upright, returning to the starting position.
After all reps are completed, switch sides and repeat the movement, then return the barbell to the rack.

steps: Position yourself on the ground with legs fully extended and hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart at the level of your chest.

Exhale and push forward with your hands to rock yourself back into the starting position.

name: Single Leg Box Squat
notes: If you cannot squat low enough, start with a higher box, and gradually work your way down to a smaller one.

primary_muscle_groups.description: Muscles spanning the front of your thigh.

steps: Position a box behind you and stand with feet shoulder-width apart with your arms raised at shoulder-level in front of you.
Raise one leg slightly in front of you while keeping it straight and balance on the leg that remains on the ground.
Inhale and break at the hips, sitting down and back in the direction of the box while simultaneously bringing your raised leg forward as you squat down.
Continue until your butt makes contact with the box while your raised leg is still in the air.
Exhale and press through your heel and midfoot while keeping your foot firmly planted until you stand upright, returning to the starting position.
After all reps are completed, switch sides and repeat the movement. 10 reps prescribed means you should perform 10 reps on each side (20 total).

Continue to lower yourself down until your hands touch your heel.
Exhale and extend your planted leg while bringing your raised leg forward to return to the starting position.
After all reps are completed, switch sides and repeat the movement. 10 reps prescribed means you should perform 10 reps on each side (20 total).

steps: Stand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart and arms extended by your sides.
Inhale and squat down while leaning forward with a straight torso, keeping your back flat.
Continue until you can place your hands on the ground in front of you shoulder-width apart and at the level of your shoulders.
Exhale and keep your hands on the ground while you kick off with your legs, extending them behind you to enter a push up position.
Inhale then exhale, raising one leg out to the side, rotating and bending it while lowering your torso down simultaneously.
Inhale then bring the leg back while straightening your arms and pushing up before doing the same with your other leg.
Exhale then jump forward, catching yourself in a squatting position with your hands on the ground.
Stand upright to jump and then catch yourself, returning to the starting position.

steps: Orient yourself on the machine, placing your butt, lower back, upper back, and head all firmly in the seat.

Grip the side bars, placing your feet parallel to each other shoulder-width apart with your toes pointed forward so that only the balls of your feet and your toes are in contact with the plate of the machine.
unlock the safety mechanism so that the machine can freely move.

primary_muscle_groups.description: Largest portion of your chest, spanning from your sternum to your shoulder. It takes up a majority of your chest and is multiple times larger than your clavicular head.
Smallest portion of your chest, spanning from your clavicle to your shoulder. It takes up a very small area of your chest and is multiple times smaller than your sternal head.

steps: Wrap a band around a power rack or pole at shoulder-level and stand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart, facing a direction perpendicular to the band.
With the arm closest to the band held at shoulder-level and bent, grip the band.
Exhale and press diagonally forward and inward across your body while keeping your arm at shoulder-level, not allowing its height to change or your torso to rotate.
Continue to press your arm diagonally until it is fully extended.
Inhale and allow your arm to bend back to the starting position, continuing to prevent your torso from rotating.
After all reps are completed, switch sides and repeat the movement. 10 reps prescribed means you should perform 10 reps on each side (20 total).

steps: Lie flat on the bench so that your head, upper back, lower back, and both feet are firmly pressed against the bench and ground at all points.
Grab the barbell on the rack at slightly wider than shoulder-width by extending your arms and bring it forward until it is over the middle of your chest and your arms are fully extended.
Inhale and lower the barbell towards the middle of your chest.
Continue lowering the barbell until just before it makes contact with your chest.
Exhale and push the barbell upwards returning to the starting position, while keeping your feet, lower back, upper back, and head firmly planted.
After all reps are completed, return the barbell to the rack.

primary_muscle_groups.description: Muscles spanning the front of your thigh.

steps: Orient yourself on the machine, placing your butt, lower back, upper back, and head all firmly in the seat.
Adjust the safety mechanism to determine your desired range of motion, selecting one where your thighs make at least a 90º angle with your lower legs.
With your hands gripping the side bars, feet parallel to each other shoulder-width apart and toes pointed slightly outward, unlock the safety mechanism so that the machine can freely move.
Exhale, extending your legs forward and straightening them.
Continue to extend your legs while keeping all body parts firmly in the seat and your feet flatly pressed against the machine until your legs are straight.
Inhale and lower your legs down, allowing them to bend in order to return to the starting position.
Relock the safety mechanism to hold the machine in place so that you can safely exit.

Exhale and raise your chest up while keeping your lower back on the ground.

Inhale and lower yourself back down slowly, returning to the starting position.

steps: Wrap a band around a power rack or pole several inches above its lowest point.
With the band secured around your feet, lie on the floor facing the ceiling with your legs extended in front of you on the floor.
Exhale and raise your legs while curling your knees toward your head, until your thighs are directly above your hips.
Inhale briefly then exhale and kick your legs upwards while allowing your butt and lower back to come off the floor.
Continue until your legs are fully extended overhead.
Inhale and lower your legs and butt down until your butt is firmly on the ground and your legs are bent with your thighs directly above your hips.
Exhale briefly then inhale and kick your legs forward, returning to the starting position.

Lift the barbell from the rack by partially standing up and taking a step back while squeezing the bar tightly and keeping it rested over your upper back.
Inhale and with feet pointed slightly outwards break at your hips, sitting down and allowing your torso to come moderately forward while keeping it straight.
Continue until your thighs are at least parallel to the floor.
Exhale and push through your heels to return to the starting position.
After all reps are completed, walk forward to return the barbell to the rack.

steps: Place a barbell on the floor and position yourself over the center of it with your feet shoulder-width apart and shins about 1 inch away from the barbell.
Maintaining a straight back, bend down with your legs while leaning forward and position your hands on the barbell shoulder-width apart with an overhand grip and fully extended arms.
Exhale and push through your feet while extending your legs to begin lifting the barbell while maintaining a flat back.

After the barbell passes your knees, drive through your hips while continuing to extend your legs until you are standing fully upright with your torso in line with the rest of your body. Do not lean further back than this.
Inhale and begin to lower the barbell by bending your legs and lowering your torso while focusing on maintaining a flat back above all else.
Returning to the starting position, rest the barbell on the floor for 1 second before beginning your next rep.

primary_muscle_groups.description: Upper abdomen, from just above your belly button to your sternum. The upper half of the "six pack" abs.

steps: Wrap a band around a power rack or pole 1-2 feet above head level.
Position yourself on your knees in front of it while gripping either end of the band with an underhand grip at shoulder-level.
Exhale and curl your body forward while keeping your knees firmly in place on the ground and your hands at shoulder-level. Do not allow your arms to help you with the movement.
Continue curling your body forward until you are no longer able to do so without the help of your arms or your knees leaving the ground.
Inhale and allow your torso to straighten, returning to the starting position.

equipment.description: When gripping dumbbells, make sure you position your hands in the middle of the bar and not at the end next to the plates.
equipment.name: Dumbbells

muscle_groups.description: Outer portion of your bicep.
A group of muscles on the outside and sides of your lower arm.
Inner portion of your bicep.
Center region of your back, spanning from the pelvis to just below the neck. However, parts of it are hidden beneath other muscles. The lower portion is the most visible.

name: Hammer Curl
notes: Squeeze your biceps as you curl the dumbbells upwards for added benefit.

primary_muscle_groups.description: Outer portion of your bicep.
A group of muscles on the outside and sides of your lower arm.

steps: Stand upright with your hands by the side of your body with palms facing inwards, holding one dumbbell in each hand with a neutral grip.
Keeping your upper arms by your side, exhale and raise the dumbbells towards your shoulders by flexing your arm and maintaining a neutral grip. Avoid using your legs or back to lift the dumbbell.
Continue until your arms are fully flexed and the dumbbells cannot be curled any further.
Inhale and lower the dumbbells back down, returning to the starting position.

equipment.description: This means that the only thing you need to successfully perform the exercise is your body. No other equipment is needed.
equipment.name: Bodyweight Only

muscle_groups.description: Outer sides of your abdomen.
Upper abdomen, from just above your belly button to your sternum. The upper half of the "six pack" abs.
Lower abdomen, from just above your belly button to your pubis. The lower half of the "six pack" abs.
Muscles spanning the front of your thigh.

name: Air Bike
notes: Do not pull on your head with your arms. Doing so can lead to later discomfort in your neck. It is best to focus on using your abs to raise you up, consciously ignoring your arms.

primary_muscle_groups.description: Outer sides of your abdomen.
Upper abdomen, from just above your belly button to your sternum. The upper half of the "six pack" abs.

steps: Lie flat on the ground with your hands behind your head, legs raised directly above your hips, and bent so that your lower leg and upper leg make a 90 degree angle.

Maintaining this angle, exhale and raise your torso with a twisting motion in the direction of your opposite knee while simultaneously drawing that knee in towards your torso. Do not bring your head forward, keep it in line with your torso.
Continue until you can no longer raise your torso with a twisting motion any longer.
Inhale and slowly return to the starting position by lowering your torso and pushing your leg away from your torso.
Switch sides and repeat the movement.

equipment.description: These bands are usually the easiest to grip. If none are available, you can use a loop band instead.
equipment.name: Handle Band

muscle_groups.description: Outer portion of your bicep.
Inner portion of your bicep.
A group of muscles on the inside of your lower arm.
Center region of your back, spanning from the pelvis to just below the neck. However, parts of it are hidden beneath other muscles. The lower portion is the most visible.

name: Band Curl
notes: For added benefit, hold the top position of the rep for an extra 1 second before lowering your arms to return to the starting position.

primary_muscle_groups.description: Outer portion of your bicep.

steps: Stand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart over the middle of a band and your arms by your side holding it with an underhand grip.
Keeping your upper arm by your side, exhale and raise the band up toward your shoulder by bending your arm. Avoid using your legs or back to lift.
Continue until your arm is fully flexed and the band cannot be curled any further.
Inhale and lower the band back down, returning to the starting position.
